In [[medieval England]], '''avera''' and '''inward''' (or '''inguard''') were feudal obligations assessed against a [[royal demesne]].  The terms refer to various services rendered to the crown in lieu of payment in coin.<ref name=Domesday/>  ''Avera'' is connected with carrying items by horse,<ref name=Domesday>{{cite book | title=The Domesday Geography of South-East England | volume=3 | series=Domesday Geography of England | author1=H. C. Darby | author2=Eila M. J. Campbell | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | year=1962 | isbn=0-521-04770-6 | page=72 }}</ref> or possibly ploughing<ref>{{cite book | title=England under the Norman occupation | author=James Morgan | publisher=Williams and Norgate | year=1858 | page=135 }}</ref> or both.<ref name=ellis/> ''Inward'' is probably the provision of a bodyguard during a royal visit:<ref>{{cite book | title=The origins of Hertfordshire | series=Origins of the Shire | author=Tom Williamson | publisher=Manchester University Press | year=2000 | isbn=0-7190-4491-X | page=103 }}</ref> in Anglo-Saxon England it could be claimed by a [[sheriff]].<ref>{{cite journal | title=The Office of Sheriff in the Anglo-Saxon Period | author=William A. Morris | journal=The English Historical Review | volume=31 | number=121 | date=Jan 1916 | pages=20–40 | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | jstor=550697 | doi=10.1093/ehr/xxxi.cxxi.20}}</ref>  The services could usually be commuted to a monetary payment: in [[Hertfordshire]] avera could be commuted for fourpence.<ref>{{cite book | title=The kalendar of Abbot Samson of Bury St. Edmunds: and related documents | volume=84 | series=Camden third series | editor=Ralph Henry Carless Davis |publisher=Royal Historical Society | year=1954  | page=xxxv}}</ref>  The services were usually found in the eastern counties, especially [[Cambridgeshire]] and [[Hertfordshire]],<ref name=ellis>{{cite book | title=A general introduction to Domesday Book: accompanied by indexes of the tenants in chief, and under tenants, at the time of the survey, as wall as of the holders of lands ...  Volume 1 | author=Sir Henry Ellis | authorlink=Henry Ellis (librarian) | year=1833 | page=263 | publisher=Commission on the Public Records }}</ref> due from [[sokemen]].<ref name=vch>{{cite book | chapter=Hitchin: Introduction and manors | title=A History of the County of Hertford | volume=3 | year=1912 | pages=3–12 | url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43569 | accessdate=15 September 2010 }}</ref>  In Hertfordshire, inward is found only in the manor of [[Hitchin]].<ref name=vch/>

