[[File:World same-sex adoption laws.svg|right|thumb|300px|Legal status of adoption by same-sex couples around the world: {{legend|#800080|Joint adoption allowed}} {{legend|#ba75ff|Second-parent adoption allowed}} {{legend|#e0e0e0|No laws allowing adoption by same-sex couples}}]] The '''second-parent adoption''' or '''co-parent adoption''' is a process by which a marriage partner can [[Adoption|adopt]] her or his partner's biological or adoptive child without terminating the first legal parent's rights. This issue is of significant importance in the context of the [[LGBT adoption]].
In the United States, second-parent adoption was started by the [[National Center for Lesbian Rights]] (formerly the Lesbian Rights Project) in the mid-1980s.<ref>[http://www.nclrights.org/publications/adptn0204.htm]</ref> [[California]] (2003 <ref>''Sharon S. v. Superior Court'' (2003) 31 Cal.4th 41</ref>), [[Connecticut]], [[Illinois]], [[Maine]],<ref>[http://www.gaycitynews.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18791683&BRD=2729&PAG=461&dept_id=568860&rfi=6 gaycitynews: Maine Supreme Court:Gay couples can adopt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204165539/http://www.gaycitynews.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18791683&BRD=2729&PAG=461&dept_id=568860&rfi=6 |date=2008-02-04 }}</ref> [[Massachusetts]] (1999<ref>[http://cwhf.org/inductees/reformers/anne-stanback/#.Wi8LcUqnGCp A biofraphy] of [[Anne Stanback]]</ref>), [[New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[Vermont]] (1993<ref>{{cite news|last=Wong|first=Doris Sue|title=Vt. court rules woman may adopt children of her lesbian partner|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8232802.html|accessdate=August 8, 2013|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=June 19, 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Moats |first=David|title=Civil Wars: A Battle for Gay Marriage|year=2004|publisher=Harcourt Books|pages=96–7}}</ref> ), [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington State]] and [[Washington, D.C.]] explicitly allow second-parent adoption by same-sex couples statewide, either by statute or court ruling.<ref>[http://www.hrc.org/Template.cfm?Section=Adoption&CONTENTID=18341&TEMPLATE=/ContentManagement/ContentDisplay.cfm HRC | Page Not Found<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606080659/http://www.hrc.org/Template.cfm?Section=Adoption&CONTENTID=18341&TEMPLATE=%2FContentManagement%2FContentDisplay.cfm |date=2008-06-06 }}</ref> As of May 2007, [[Colorado]] allows second-parent adoption by same-sex couples.<ref>[http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/government/article/0,2777,DRMN_23906_5537407,00.html Gay adoption is law : Colorado Government : The Rocky Mountain News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[As of]] 2013, the [[Michigan]] law allowed second-parent adoption for married couples, while banning same-sex marriage.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/national-lgbt-groups-encouraged-court-to-delay-michigan-marr "National LGBT Groups Encouraged Court To Delay Michigan Marriage Case"] (retrieved December 11, 2017)</ref> The latter ban [[DeBoer v. Snyder|was struck down]] by the [[Supreme Court]] in 2015.
Courts in many other states have also granted second-parent adoptions to same-sex couples, though there is no statewide law or court decision that guarantees this. In fact, courts within the same state but in different jurisdictions often contradict each other in practice. {{cn|date=December 2017}}
The [[American Medical Association]] supported second parent adoption by same-sex partner,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ama-assn.org/ama/pub/about-ama/our-people/member-groups-sections/glbt-advisory-committee/ama-policy-regarding-sexual-orientation.shtml|title=H-60.940 Partner Co-Adoption, H-65.973 Health Care Disparities in Same-Sex Partner Households "AMA Policy regarding sexual orientation"|publisher=Ama-assn.org|accessdate=16 March 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019042918/http://www.ama-assn.org/ama/pub/about-ama/our-people/member-groups-sections/glbt-advisory-committee/ama-policy-regarding-sexual-orientation.page|archivedate=19 October 2013|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> stating that lack of formal recognition can cause health-care disparities for children of same-sex parents.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
The [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] supports second parent adoption. <ref name="aap-position">{{cite journal | title = Coparent or second-parent adoption by same-sex parents | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 109 | issue = 2 | pages = 339–40 | date = February 2002 | pmid = 11826219 | url = http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&amp;pmid=11826219}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Policy Statement—AAP publications retired and reaffirmed | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 124 | issue = 2 | pages = 845 | date = August 2009 | pmid = 19651598 | doi = 10.1542/peds.2009-1415 | url = http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&amp;pmid=19651598}}</ref>
In July 2011, The Ministry of Labour, Family and Social Affairs of [[Slovenia]] stated that the existing law allows for [[second-parent adoption]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policy.hu/takacs/pdf-lib/Confronting_Homophobia_in_Europe-the_book.pdf |title=Confronting Homophobia in Europe |date= |accessdate=2013-10-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/first-adoption-by-gay-partner-of-child-s-parent|title=First Adoption by Gay Partner of Child's Parent|last=|first=|date=|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=|access-date=2017-02-26}}</ref>
In the context of [[LGBT adoption and parenting in Australia]], {{as of|2008}}, the best option was to apply to the [[Family Court of Australia]] for a parenting order, as ‘other people significant to the care, welfare and development’ of the child. It provides an important "status quo" if the birth mother were to die, preventing other family members from taking immediate custody of the child.<ref>{{cite web |title=Same Sex, Same Entitlements |publisher=Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission |url=http://www.humanrights.gov.au/human_rights/samesex/report/Ch_5.html |accessdate=13 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Is second parent adoption possible in Australia? |publisher=Gay & Lesbian Rights Lobby |url=http://www.glrl.org.au/issues/relationship_qa.htm#Q4_1 |accessdate=13 May 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719183625/http://www.glrl.org.au/issues/relationship_qa.htm%23Q4_1 |archivedate=19 July 2008 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
